PCL102H1-S-20189.courseDescription: This course introduces students to the processes and strategies for discovering new drugs with a special focus on current and emerging approaches for the rational design of drugs that are both effective and safe.
PCL102H1-S-20189.webTimetableInstructions: Student inquiries should be directed to the course coordinator: Dr. Rebecca Laposa, rebecca.laposa@utoronto.ca.  Please do not contact the listed instructors for course-related questions.

PCL200H1-F-20189.courseDescription: Lectures introduce students to prescribed and illicit drugs that affect the brain. Lectures cover drug pharmacology and explain how drugs alter mood, perception, cognition, and arousal by affecting different aspects of brain function. The societal impact of these prescribed and illicit drugs is also discussed
PCL200H1-F-20189.webTimetableInstructions:
Student inquiries should be directed to the course coordinator: Dr. Amy Ramsey, a.ramsey@utoronto.ca.  Please do not contact the listed instructors for course-related questions.

Please note this is a breadth course for students either outside of the Life Sciences or for students in year 1  interested in gaining an appreciation for drugs and the brain.

PCL201H1-S-20189.courseTitle: Introduction to Pharmacology and Pharmacokinetic Principles
PCL201H1-S-20189.courseDescription: A general introduction to the principles of pharmacology and pharmacokinetics. Topics include chemical (drug) absorption, distribution, biotransformation, elimination; the calculation of dosages and pharmacokinetic parameters, variability in drug response, adverse drug reactions and special interest topics.
PCL201H1-S-20189.corequisite: Recommended Co-requisites: BIO230H1/(BIO240H1, BIO241H1), CHM247H1/CHM249H1, PSL300H1/PSL301H1
PCL201H1-S-20189.webTimetableInstructions:
Student inquiries should be directed to the course coordinator: Dr. Michelle Arnot, michelle.arnot@utoronto.ca. Please do not contact the listed instructors for course-related questions. 

Students in either Subject POsT code AEESCBASCO BASc-Engineering Sci (Nano Eng) or 	 
AEESCBASEB BASc in Eng Sci (Biomedical) will be provided exemption from required pre-requisite courses. Please contact course coordinator

PCL297H1-F-20189.courseDescription: A formal opportunity to gain hands-on experience and develop their skills within a research laboratory setting. Students will have a chance to become familiar and efficient at good lab practices, develop critical thinking and evaluation skills while applying their knowledge and developing trouble shooting skills to practical research questions. This course is Pass/Fail. Not eligible for CR/NCR option.

PCL302H1-F-20189.courseDescription: Topics include biological action of drugs on membranes, enzymes, receptors, neural and hormonal systems, transmission and modulation.
PCL302H1-F-20189.webTimetableInstructions: Student inquiries should be directed to the course coordinator: Dr. Jane Mitchell, jane.mitchell@utoronto.ca. Please do not contact the listed instructors for course-related questions.

PCL345H1-S-20189.courseDescription: Lecturers use their own research to demonstrate how they approach a biological question. The lectures emphasize why one approach is chosen over other possible approaches, and explain the strengths and limitations of techniques. Following the one-hour lecture there is an interactive discussion of the experimental approach covered in the lecture.
PCL345H1-S-20189.prerequisite: BCH210H1; completion of at least 10 FCE
PCL345H1-S-20189.webTimetableInstructions: Student inquiries should be directed to the course coordinator: Dr. Ana Andreazza, ana.andreazza@utoronto.ca.  Please do not contact the listed instructors for course-related questions.

PCL362H1-F-20189.courseDescription: Toxicological problems encountered in animals and humans; biochemical mechanisms and clinical factors of toxicological significance; models of drug-related diseases.
PCL362H1-F-20189.prerequisite: BCH210H1, BIO230H1/(BIO240H1, BIO241H1), CHM247H1/CHM249H1, PCL201H1 or Permission of the Course Coordinator
PCL362H1-F-20189.webTimetableInstructions: Student inquiries should be directed to the course coordinator: Dr. Peter Wells, pg.wells@utoronto.ca. Please do not contact the listed instructors for course-related questions.

PCL366H1-F-20189.courseDescription: Through practical hands-on laboratory experiments and tutorials, students will be introduced to some basic experimental techniques and laboratory skills that are used within pharmacology and toxicology research. (Ancillary lab fee $25)
PCL366H1-F-20189.webTimetableInstructions: Student inquiries should be directed to the course coordinator: Dr. Anita Hamadanizadeh, anita.hamadanizadeh@utoronto.ca. Please do not contact the listed instructors for course-related questions.

PCL389H1-F-20189.courseTitle: Understanding the Role of Pharmacology and Toxicology in Society
PCL389H1-F-20189.courseDescription: This service learning course explores issues surrounding the effects that pharmaceuticals and chemicals have in society. Specifically, it integrates pharmacology and toxicology with social, health and political issues as they relate to drug abuse and addiction. Students are required to interact and work with community partners during the semester (approx 20hrs). Classroom discussions will integrate community experiences with lecture material.
PCL389H1-F-20189.webTimetableInstructions: Student inquiries should be directed to the course coordinator: Dr. Michelle Arnot, michelle.arnot@utoronto.ca. Please do not contact the listed instructors for course-related questions.

PCL402H1-F-20189.courseTitle: Pharmacology and Toxicology in Drug Development
PCL402H1-F-20189.courseDescription: This course provides the basic principles of drug development, with a primary focus on the application of fundamental principles of pharmacology and toxicology to the design and conduct of early phase clinical trials. This is the phase of the drug development process where much of the innovation and science occurs.
PCL402H1-F-20189.webTimetableInstructions: Student inquiries should be directed to the course coordinator: Dr. Rebecca Laposa, rebecca.laposa@utoronto.ca. Please do not contact the listed instructors for course-related questions.

PCL461H1-S-20189.courseDescription: Advanced laboratory exercises and discussions through tutorials and presentations in selected areas of pharmacology. Enrollment in this course is generally restricted to students enrolled in the Pharmacology Specialist and Pharmacology and Biomedical Toxicology Specialist programs. (Ancillary lab fee $25).
PCL461H1-S-20189.webTimetableInstructions: Student inquiries should be directed to the course coordinator: Dr. Anita Hamadanizadeh, anita.hamadanizadeh@utoronto.ca. Please do not contact the listed instructors for course-related questions.

PCL469H1-S-20189.courseDescription: A culmination of pharmacological principles discussing concepts of drug properties and their interactions within the body. The mechanism of action, pharmacological properties including clinical use and adverse effects of drugs acting on the autonomic nervous systems, cardiovascular, renal, respiratory, gastrointestinal and endocrine systems will be examined. Critical evaluation of primary literature and examination of clinical problem-based case studies will be integrated with lecture material through small group sessions.
PCL469H1-S-20189.webTimetableInstructions: Student inquiries should be directed to the course coordinator: Dr. Michelle Arnot, michelle.arnot@utoronto.ca. Please do not contact the listed instructors for course-related questions.

PCL470H1-F-20189.courseDescription: A culmination of pharmacological principles discussing concepts of drug properties and their interactions within the body. The mechanism of action, pharmacological properties including clinical use and adverse effects of drugs acting on the central nervous systems and immunological system; antimicrobial and cancer chemotherapeutic agents as well as the potential therapeutic use of endogenous/herbal compounds will be examined. Critical evaluation of primary literature and examination of clinical problem-based case studies will be integrated with lecture material through small group sessions.
PCL470H1-F-20189.webTimetableInstructions: Student inquiries should be directed to the course coordinator: Dr. Ali Salahpour, ali.salahpour@utoronto.ca. Please do not contact the listed instructors for course-related questions.

PCL472Y1-S-20189.courseDescription: This course affords students an opportunity for hands-on research experience in a laboratory or applied pharmacology setting. Students will work under the supervision of a faculty member and will submit a final written report and oral presentation. Enrollment is limited and requires permission from the Department of Pharmacology and Toxicology. It is the student’s responsibility to secure a placement with an approved supervisor before the course begins (a list of potential supervisors can be obtained from the Department of Pharmacology and Toxicology). Students will be registered in the course once their ballot form (obtained from the Department of Pharmacology and Toxicology) is signed by an approved supervisor and approved by the Department of Pharmacology and Toxicology. Students are expected to spend approximately 200 hours towards this project but this will be project/supervisor dependent. Not eligible for CR/NCR option.
PCL472Y1-S-20189.prerequisite: PCL201H1, PCL302H1, PCL366H1, STA288H1/ PCL376H1, and permission of Department
PCL472Y1-S-20189.webTimetableInstructions:
Students enroll in this course through the Department. 

Please contact Dr Laposa at pharmtox.research.project@utoronto.ca

PCL473Y1-Y-20189.courseDescription: This course explores several contemporary topics in biomedical and environmental toxicology with emphasis on how chemicals affect human health.  Lectures cover principles of toxicology, the mechanisms of toxicity of a wide variety of toxic agents and the associated toxicities, methodologies used to examine chemical toxicities, risk assessment, and the applications of toxicology. Not eligible for CR/NCR option.
PCL473Y1-Y-20189.prerequisite: BCH210H1, PCL201H1, PCL302H1, PCL362H1 or Permission of the Course Coordinator
PCL473Y1-Y-20189.webTimetableInstructions: Student inquiries should be directed to the course coordinator: Dr. Peter McPherson, peter.mcpherson@utoronto.ca. Please do not contact the listed instructors for course-related questions.

PCL475Y1-Y-20189.courseDescription: Major neuro-psychiatric disease syndromes: clinical pathology and neuronal abnormalities; CNS drugs: theories and mechanisms of action.
PCL475Y1-Y-20189.webTimetableInstructions: Student inquiries should be directed to the course coordinator: Dr. Mac Burnham, mac.burnham@utoronto.ca. Please do not contact the listed instructors for course-related questions.

PCL477H1-F-20189.courseTitle: The DNA Damage Response in Pharmacology and Toxicology
PCL477H1-F-20189.courseDescription: Many anticancer drugs and environmental agents exert their cytotoxic effects through DNA damage. This course explores specific pharmacological and toxicological agents that damage DNA and discusses how mammalian cells respond to this DNA damage.
PCL477H1-F-20189.webTimetableInstructions: Student inquiries should be directed to the course coordinator: Dr. Peter McPherson, peter.mcpherson@utoronto.ca. Please do not contact the listed instructors for course-related questions.

PCL481H1-S-20189.courseTitle: The Molecular and Biochemical Basis of Toxicology
PCL481H1-S-20189.courseDescription: The biochemical principles and molecular mechanisms underlying the toxicity of drugs and foreign agents. The sequence of events at the molecular level leading to impairment of cell function and the factors which determine and affect toxicity.
PCL481H1-S-20189.webTimetableInstructions: Student inquiries should be directed to the course coordinator: Dr. Denis Grant, denis.grant@utoronto.ca. Please do not contact the listed instructors for course-related questions.

PCL486H1-S-20189.courseDescription: This course will expand on both classical and cutting edge pharmacological strategies proposed to mitigate the consequences of altered signal transduction in cancer. Students will have the opportunity to develop knowledge on these molecular events and how they can be targeted to improve clinical outcomes. Students will integrate lecture material with assigned readings and assignments.
PCL486H1-S-20189.webTimetableInstructions: Student inquiries should be directed to the course coordinator: Dr. Leonardo Salmena, leonardo.salmena@utoronto.ca.  Please do not contact the listed instructors for course-related questions.

PCL490H1-S-20189.courseTitle: Advanced Topics in Pharmacology and Toxicology
PCL490H1-S-20189.courseDescription: An opportunity to expand on innovative and unique topics in Pharmacology and Toxicology that are not already extensively addressed. The course will reveal the dynamic nature of the field and the diverse interests of our faculty. Students will be introduced to leading edge topics and research within the discipline of Pharmacology and Toxicology.
PCL490H1-S-20189.prerequisite: PCL302H1, and one of STA288H1/ STA220H1/ PCL376H1
